# Drugs Bind to [Neurotransmitter Transporters](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurotransmitter_transporter) (22)

**Serotonin pathways in the brain**
* [Raphe nuclei](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raphe_nuclei) release serotonin to the rest of the brain.
* Raphe nuclei are in two systems
  - Rostral and Caudal
* Serotonergic means "related to the neurotransmitter serotonin".

**3 classes of proteins transport ions across membranes**
* Passive Transport
  - Channel Proteins  
  - Ion Coupled Transporter (play a major role in neurotransmitter transport)  
* Active transport
  - requires energy from ATP  
  - Ion Pumps (also important in neurotransmitter transport) 

**Plasma Membrane neurotransmitter transport into cell** 
* ATP driven Sodium pump increases Sodium concentration in cell
* Sodium (Na+) coupled neurotransmitter transporter
  (Sodium ions flow out of cell, neurotransmitter flows into cell
* Process can be reversed
* Performs two major functions 
<ol>
<li>Terminate action of Neurotransmitter</li>
<li>Replenish neurotransmitter in presynaptic terminal of neuron</li>
</ol>

**Vesicle transport** 
* gets neurotransmitter into synaptic vesicles (SV)
* ATP driven Proton pump increases protons within SV
* proton coupled neurotransmitter transporter
  (Protons flow out of SV, neurotransmitter flows into SV
* Process can be reversed 

**MDMA or Amphetamines Release Transmitter into the External Medium**
* inhibits uptake of dopamine into presynaptic terminal
* causes release of dopamine (DA) from presynaptic terminals

**Method to detect dopamine**
* Carbon-ﬁber electrodes can be used to make sensitive current measurements
* This method is called Cyclic voltammetry

**Dopamine transporter (DAT) knockout mice experiment**
* Experiment to determine effect of amphetamine on normal mice and mice that lack dopamine transporter
* DAT knockout means deletion of a gene that expresses dopamine trasnporter protein
* Normal mice: after release of amphetamine there is a gradual increase of extracellular dopamine
* DAT knockout mice: after release of amphetamine; no change in extracellular dopamine   

**Sodium (Na+) coupled cell membrane neurotransmitter transporter major targets for drugs of therapy and abuse** 
* serotonin transporter 
- Antidepressants (Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors or SSRI)  
- Recreational drug: MDMA 
* dopamine transporter
- Attention-deficit disorder (amphetamine)  
- Recreational drug: cocaine, amphetamines
 
