# Neurotransmitter Transporters as Molecules (23)
* discussion of neurotransmitter transporter as proteins
* counting neurotransmitter transporter  

**“Alternating Access” Model for ion-coupled transporters**
* How do ion coupled transporters work?
* Move an ion and a small molecule
* transporter protein "cycles" between two conformations which moves molecules between two compartments
* symport moves molecules to the same compartment
* antiport moves molecules to opposite compartments


**Fluoxetine Bound to LeuT, a Bacterial Homologue of Neurotransmitter Transporters**
* the bacterial protein shown is a transporter that is analogous to neurotransmitter transporter 
* it is a static view, not dynamic

**[SSRIs](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Selective_serotonin_reuptake_inhibitor) bind tightly to, and stabilize, intermediate state(s) of the serotonin transporter**
* The experiment describes the dynamics of the “Alternating Access” Model
* ion-coupled transporters behave like ion channel with gates on either end
* Sodium, potassium and chloride ions can be used
* Sometimes both gates can be stuck open - like an ion channel
* [SSRIs](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Selective_serotonin_reuptake_inhibitor)get the transporter "stuck", preventing it from functioning

**The GAT1 inhibitor, tiagabine, is used for epilepsy.**
* one type GABA transporter is caled GAT1 
* tiagabine slows GAT1 transport of GABA, which prolongs lifetime of GABA, allows GABA inhibition to increase, decreasing neuron firing
* developed method to count GAT1

**[cerebellum](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebellum), rich in GABA inhibition**
* Looked at molecular layer, [Purkinje cell layer](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Purkinje_cell), and [granule cell layer](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Granule_cell_(cerebellum))


**How to localize and quantify GABA transporters**
* Take the gene of GABA transporter and append [green fluorescent protein (GFP)](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_fluorescent_protein)
* the protein expressed is a GABA transporter that fluoresces green and can be counted


**Brain of GABA Transporter-GFP ‘Knock-in” Mouse**
* need to make a strain of mice with the gene that has GABA transporter with GFP
* called a knock-in because a gene has been added
* GABA transporter with GFP expressed throughout mouse brain

**GAT1-GFP expression in cerebellum**
* The highest density (most green) region of the cerebellum is at junction of basket cells and Purkinje cell layer
* this is the pinceaux region
* at the molecular level, there are about 1000 GABA transporter per square micron
* An example of how neuroscientists study the targets for drugs
  
