# Recreational  Drugs: Overview (24)
* Apply what we learn to certain key classes of drug action

**Recreational drugs**
* Recreational drugs are not equal to addictive drugs are not equal to abused drugs are not equal to illegal drugs
* but there is some overlaps
* We will study a constellation of nine drugs, mostly low molecular weight
* [morphine](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morphine), [tetrahydrocannabinol](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahydrocannabinol), [ethanol](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethanol)  
* [caffeine](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caffeine), [phencyclidine](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phencyclidine), [LSD](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LSD)  
* [nicotine](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicotine), [cocaine](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cocaine), [amphetamine](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amphetamine)

**Sources of recreational drugs**
* Most come from plants
* Drugs protected plants from herbivores

**Cocaine in the test tube and Mechanisms of entry, exemplified by cocaine**
* Cocaine base is uncharged (free base or crack) which permeates membranes
* Cocaine is reprotonated, the charged form in the brain acts on the dopamine transporter

**Routes into the body**
* The various routes include eating/drinking, inhaling, smoking, and injecting
* The best routes depend on the chemistry of the molecule.
  
